Project description¶

The Emergency Call Data project is a comprehensive and data-driven initiative aimed at extracting valuable insights and enhancing decision-making processes from emergency call data (sourced from Kaggle). This project involves the analysis of emergency call records to uncover patterns, trends, and critical information that can significantly impact emergency response strategies, resource allocation, and public safety measures.

During the course of this project, we will extract meaningful insights from the data relating to emergency calls using the following steps: Data transformation and preparation, Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), Temporal Analysis, Reporting and Visualization.

Creating new features¶

In the title column there are "Reasons/Departments" specified before the title code. These are EMS, Fire, and Traffic. We can use .apply() command with a custom lambda expression to create a new column called "Reason" that contains this string value. For example, if the title column value is EMS: BACK PAINS/INJURY, the Reason column value would be EMS.

In [ ]:
df['Reason'] = df['title'].apply(lambda title: title.split(':')[0])

What is the most common Reason for a 911 call based on this new column:¶

In [16]:

Out[16]:
EMS        48877
Traffic    35695
Fire       14920
Name: Reason, dtype: int64

Now let us begin to focus on time information. For instance, lets check the data type of the objects in the timeStamp column:¶

In [20]:
type(df['timeStamp'].iloc[0])
Out[20]:
str

The timestamps are still strings. We can use the [pd.to_datetime] to convert the column from strings to DateTime objects.¶

In [21]:
df['timeStamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df['timeStamp'])

We can now grab specific attributes from a Datetime object by calling them. For example:¶

time = df['timeStamp'].iloc[0]
time.hour

Now that the timestamp column are actually DateTime objects, use .apply() to create 3 new columns called Hour, Month, and Day of Week. We can create these columns based off of the timeStamp column.¶

In [22]:
df['Hour'] = df['timeStamp'].apply(lambda time: time.hour)
df['Day of Week'] = df['timeStamp'].apply(lambda time: time.dayofweek)
df['Month'] = df['timeStamp'].apply(lambda time: time.month)
In [ ]:
#Notice how the Day of Week is an integer 0-6. Use the .map() with this dictionary to map the actual string names to the day of the week
In [23]:
dmap = {0:'Mon',1:'Tue',2:'Wed',3:'Thu',4:'Fri',5:'Sat',6:'Sun'}
In [24]:
df['Day of Week'] = df['Day of Week'].map(dmap)

Next steps:¶

This project is anticipated to yield several significant outcomes such as:

  1. Improved Emergency Response: Insights gained from the analysis will help emergency response agencies allocate resources more effectively and respond promptly to critical situations.

  2. Enhanced Public Safety Measures: Data-driven recommendations can lead to better-informed public safety policies and strategies, ultimately contributing to the well-being of the community.

  3. Optimized Resource Allocation: By understanding patterns and trends, authorities can allocate personnel and equipment where they are most needed.

  4. Targeted Public Awareness Campaigns: Insights into demographic and geographic trends can inform public awareness campaigns and educational initiatives on safety and emergency preparedness.

This project can also be viewed on Github
